§aSodium Persulfate§r can be used in §9Ore Processing§r in the §3Chemical Bath§r, to get various bonus outputs you would not normally obtained. It is completely optional, but pretty rewarding.


§lBut§r the real topic of this Quest is here:
§aSodium Persulfate§r and §aIron III Chloride§r are used to make cheaper §9Good Circuit Boards§r, as it cuts the Silver amount by a factor of four.
They are also §drequired§r to make §9Plastic Circuit Boards§r.

Making §aSodium Persulfate§r will yield §aHydrochloric Acid§r as a coproduct, which you may re-use to make §aIron III Chloride§r. This should the best approach right now, but the decision is entirely yours.
With more automation later in the game, Iron III Chloride will be the cheaper and more straight forward path.


This Quest can be completed with §eeither§r Fluid.

§oAlright, you have made a Polymer already, how about you make another one?§r

§aPolyvinyl Chloride (PVC)§r is the 3rd-most produced plastic in real life. Here, it can be used in place of Polyethylene in production of §aPlastic Circuit Boards§r and other items to increase the yield.

PVC item pipes also have the §6highest throughput§r available for a while, if your setups need it.

§9Pro tip:§r the fluid form of PVC is never used in base GTCEu, so feel free to solidify all of it into sheets.

§oRemember the Ore Processing Quest referencing the Electrolyzer? It told you that you had to wait until MV, so here we are.§r

The Advanced Electrolyzer allows you to decompose §6all§r Dusts. This will make getting materials such as §aAluminium§o§§ a lot easier!

Clay is an extremely §mbalanced§r useful material for electrolysis.
All four output Dusts are great.

You will need §a§ra total of §a416 Clay Dust§r for this quest. You may also want to look into other sources of similar materials, such as §aSodalite§r. Check JEI for some ideas.

You should use Sodium and/or Lithium to make some §6MV Batteries§r.

The §3Assembling Machine§r is a staple for every Tier, an important goal to unlock more recipes and progress further into the Age.

The §bMV §3Assembling Machine§r unlocks §eTransistors§§, §eCapacitors§r and §eInductors§r, used for the next tiers of Circuits.

§oMore upgrades...! §r

The §bMV§a Cutting Machine§r is required to cut §7Silicon Boules§r to prepare them for §aLaser Engraving§r.

I recommend you run this machine with §dLubricant§r, to cut down on the processing time. Lubricant can be brewed from an Oil and §aTalc§r, §2Soapstone§r or §cRedstone§r.

The §3Laser Engraver§r engraves patterns into §9Silicon Wafers§r based on the type of §9Lens§r it is given. After the wafers are engraved, they must be passed through a §3Cutting Machine§r to turn them into components ready to be put into Circuits.
Higher tier Engravers can etch more complex wafers for more efficient Circuits.

For now, the §aIntegrated Logic Circuit§r will be the one of interest, but the others will become important for higher tier Circuits.

You have unlocked a new Tier of Circuits!
The Integrated Logic Circuit is an alternate §aLV Circuit§r, which can be upgraded to §aMV§r, and then §aHV§r.


§9Note:§r This is not a strict upgrade to the cost of Circuits, you would need to get to the next Tier for that, just slightly further down in the MV Age. Why would you need this Circuit type then? You need it to get to §6HV circuits§r.


§bLore:§r The circuit progression in GTCEu is mostly based on GT5u's progression. However it has been rebalanced to not be as painful, specifically this circuit tier which was a complete bait!
The MV Circuit for the Integrated Tier.

§oAlright, technically HV Circuit and Stainless Steel means you can move to HV... but let's not rush things.§r

The first thing you should probably make with them is a §3MV Circuit Assembler§r, to unlock the new tier of Circuits right away; they are the §dreal payoff§r.

At this point, you have all the tools available to you to make Plastic Boards.

The recipes are pretty long, so I recommend processing large batches in two dedicated §3Chemical Reactors§r.

§oI'm running out of things to say for these quests... I hope you get the gist of it, and don't need too many explanations.§r

As for every Tier goes, the §3Circuit Assembler§r is an essential part of the Progression, to enable a new Tier of circuits.


At this point you should use an §3Extractor§r next to your Circuit Assembler and send off dozens of stacks of §aSoldering Alloy§r Ingots.

§6The best LV Circuits§r! You will be making these for the remainder of the game.

Eventually (in EV Age), they will become even cheaper.

§6The best MV Circuits§r! You will be making these for the remainder of the game.

Eventually (in IV Age), they will become even cheaper.
A Circuit Component, that you can now make thanks the §3MV Assembler§r.
A Circuit Component, that you can now make thanks the §3MV Assembler§r.

A Circuit Component, that you can now make thanks the §3MV Assembler§r.

If you want to make them cheaper, you may smelt §aNickel-Zinc Ferrite§r.

Better HV Circuits, much §6cheaper§r and easier to make than from the previous Tier.


§6You should now be ready to move on the HV Chapter§r, unless you still need to scale up Power Production.
This one will be needed during the HV Age.

§oMore complex Alloys require higher Tier machines to mix the Dusts together.§r

The first step to dive deeper into the §bMV Age§r starts here.

§oThis quest acts as a small tutorial to automate the Electrolyzer easily!§r

The §9Smart Item Filter§r is a filter based on Recipe Maps. Placed on the side of a machine, this Filter can be selected to Electrolyzer to allow insertion of only Items that can be electrolyzed.

To circumvent the Electrolyzer getting stuck with not enough inputs, place a §cRobot Arm with a Smart Item Filter§r on your Electrolyzer. Configure it to §dImport§r, §dSupply Exact§r. Now, attach any inventory (a chest will do) on the side where you placed the Robot Arm, and TADAA! You have made automatic smart insertion to handle all Electrolyzer recipes!

§9Note:§r The Robot Arm has to do Item transfer itself for its functionality to work! Inserting directly into the machine will ignore the Robot Arm's §dSupply Exact§r.


Now, as for the output of the Electrolyzer, you may want to route the Fluids to several Tanks, or even §3Super Tanks§r. I highly recommend §cto not void§r the Fluids, except for Water for obvious reasons.

Stainless Steel is pretty much any Steel you may encounter in everyday's life. It is extremely resilient against corrosion.§r§r

§oThe §3§oMulti Smelter§o§r§o might be the §6§omost powerful Furnace§r§o in modded Minecraft.§r

At its lowest power (Cupronickel coils and LV Voltage), it smelts 32 items in just 12 seconds - equivalent to §926.7 Furnaces§r, or 3.3 Steam Ovens!

The §3Electric Blast Furnace§r, §3Pyrolyse Oven, §b§aMulti Smelter§r, and §3Cracking Unit§r all require heating Coils. But what are the advantages of using higher tier coils?

The latter three are quite straightforward. Higher tier coils reduce the §eprocessing time§r of the Pyrolyse Oven, reduce the §9energy usage§r of the Cracking Unit, and increase the §anumber of parallel smelts§r and reduce the §9energy usage§r of the Multi Smelter.

For the EBF, things get slightly more complicated. The EBF smelts items at a certain §dtemperature§r. This is mainly determined by the tier of heating coil used - §6§r§6Cupronickel§r is §d1800K§r, §bKanthal§r is §e§d2700K§r, etc. Additionally, starting from §6HV§r, each tier of energy adds §d100K§r to the temperature.

Each EBF recipe has a certain base temperature, for example, §bAluminium§r is smelted at §d1700K§r. If the EBF temperature is not high enough, the recipe can't be done. If the EBF temperature is high enough, 2 different bonuses are applied:
§9-§r For every §d900K§r above the recipe temperature, the amount of energy required is multiplied by §a0.95x§r, which stacks.
§9-§r For every §d1800K§r above the recipe temperature, one additional overclock will be §6100% efficient§r; in other words, it will §5quadruple the speed§r, instead of doubling it.

§oThis is a guide on how to automatically route §lall§r§o your Hot Ingots to your Vacuum Freezer while keeping everything automated perfectly fine.§r

The cheap way would be to use filters, and manually add Hot Ingots one by one... That's boring! I don't like being bored, let's do something much better.


Install an §aOre Dictionary Filter§r Cover on the §3Input Bus§r of your §3Vacuum Freezer§r, open it and set to §dingotHot*§r whitelist.
From here, you have the option to route either with §9Item Pipes§r or §9AE2§r.

§9With Item Pipes§r, connect the output of your §3EBF(s)§r to the input of your §3Vacuum Freezer§r and the output dump (Chest, Crate, or ME Interface).
Make sure the Cover is on the face the pipe is connected. You can also have a §dRestrictive Pipe§r in front of the output dump to ensure the Vacuum Freezer will be prioritized.

§9With AE2§r, place a §3ME Storage Bus§r on top of your Cover and set to very §dhigh priority§r. Any hot ingots entering your ME system will automatically be moved into the Vacuum Freezer.

§oThis quest will cover all the units you will encounter in GregTech.§r

- §dFluids§r are measured in millibuckets, or mB. 1 mB is equivalent to 1 L (Litre), which is sometimes used.
One nugget or tiny dust of material is 16 mB, one ingot is 144 mB, one gem is 250 mB, one bucket is 1000 mB, and one block is 1296 mB. 

- §dTime§r is measured in ticks, or t, each of which is 1/20 of an in-game second.
Very occasionally hours (h) will be used, which is 3600 seconds, or 72k ticks.

- §dEnergy§r is measured in Energy Units, or EU. 1 EU is equivalent to 4 RF or 2 mB of Steam. Energy is transferred in §dPackets§r, or p.

- §dPower§r is measured in EU per tick (EU/t). §dVoltage§r is measured in volts (V), which are EU/p. §dAmperage§r is measured in amperes (A), which are p/t.

§bLore§r: Before EU and RF, there were Minecraft Joules (MJ), the native energy system for BuildCraft. When EU was introduced, it was calculated that 2.5 EU = 1 MJ based on how much energy their coal generators made. Then when RF was introduced with Thermal Expansion 3, it was defined that 10 RF = 1 MJ. Therefore 1 EU = 4 RF by default.

The ore generation in §dGregTech§r is very different to vanilla or normal modded Minecraft. All ores generate in §9huge veins§r which can contain §cthousands§o§r of ore blocks!

The full extent of ore generation is explained in the Tips and Tricks tab, but here is what you need to know:

- §9Surface Rocks§r indicate a nearby type of vein. Pick one up and check §c§r§5JEI§r (press U) to see the types of ores beneath it.

- Press §4F3§r and look at the numbers after "§cChunk§r". The centers of veins are §6always§r and §6only§r where the 4th and 6th numbers (X and Z chunk coordinates) are §ba multiple of 3, plus 1§r (-8, -5, -2, 1, 4, 7...) 

- It's a good practice to make §dWaypoints§r to every vein you find with their type. You may want to come back to it several times.

Each pipe has a certain §9throughput§r in L/s (mB/s), and a §9buffer§r equivalent to its throughput in half a second. For example, a normal Bronze Fluid Pipe transfers 2,400 L/s, and has a 1,200 L buffer.
